Nagios API

Congratulations!
The Nagios API service is up and running.

You can connect to the API to retrieve status information on all Nagios hosts and services. The results are returned in JSON format for use in web applications.

Security

The Nagios API service does not include any form of security. Anyone can access the information if they know the server address and port number.

If you wish to secure the service, please use a proxy server with a proper authentication implementation (Nginx, Apache, IIS) and configure your firewall to block direct access to this service.

Retrieving data

You can retrieve the following data from the Nagios API:

/rest/v1/nagios/info
Nagios version information
/rest/v1/nagios/program
Process information regarding the running Nagios instance
/rest/v1/hosts/list
The list of hosts for which status information is available
/rest/v1/hosts/detail/{nameOrId}
Retrieve status information for the host ({nameOrId} can either be the Nagios configuration value of "host_name" or the unique identifier provided by the REST API)
/rest/v1/hosts/detail/{nameOrId}/services
List of services that are related to the host ({nameOrId} can either be the Nagios configuration value of "host_name" or the unique identifier provided by the REST API)
/rest/v1/services/list
The list of services for which status information is available
/rest/v1/services/detail/{id}
Retrieve status information for the service ({id} must be the unique identifier provided by the REST API)

The REST API will always return a (list of) objects that have the fields: "id", "type" and a list of key/value "properties". The "id" is generated by the REST API and can be used as a reference in subsequent requests. The "type" is one of the status information types that is stored by Nagios (i.e. "host", "service" or "programstatus"). The "properties" field is an array of key/values that is directly imported from the Nagios status information file. Which keys are being used depends on the Nagios version.

To improve Nagios compatibility, the REST API will not parse the Nagios status information. The status information is returned as it was given by Nagios. Applications using the REST API should be able to cope with differences in status information between Nagios versions.

Backward compatibility policy

To understand the backward compatibility policy, it is important to note that there is a difference between the REST API version, and the version of the Nagios API service. The backward compatibility policy only applies to the first.

The version of the REST API is part of the URL of the REST resource (/rest/v1/). Although additional API endpoints can be introduced with new versions of the Nagios API service, existing API endpoints will always be backward compatible within the scope of the REST API version.
